    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3642882323" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3642882323" />
    <a title="verity" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/119136112-verity"><img alt="verity" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624554642p2/119136112.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3642882323?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="verity" class="user" itemprop="url" name="verity" href="/user/show/119136112-verity">verity</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780142415436" href="/book/show/6990472-if-i-stay">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119136112-verity?shelf=2020-reads">2020-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119136112-verity?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119136112-verity?shelf=2-stars">2-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119136112-verity?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3642882323" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10734336514610937625">I have never gotten so much secondhand embarrassment from a book before <i>If I Stay. </i><br/><br/><b>Objectively, it lacks any sort of cohesive plot.</b> Instead, we’re shown memories from Mia’s past that are supposedly helping her decide if she should stay or not. I was bored to tears. <br/><br/>But here’s where the real cheese comes in. <b>Firstly, Mia herself is one of the blandest characters I’ve ever had the displeasure of reading about.</b> She fancies herself “not like the other girls”. She’s not like her family, guys. She pla</span>
  <span id="freeText10734336514610937625" style="display:none">I have never gotten so much secondhand embarrassment from a book before <i>If I Stay. </i><br /><br /><b>Objectively, it lacks any sort of cohesive plot.</b> Instead, we’re shown memories from Mia’s past that are supposedly helping her decide if she should stay or not. I was bored to tears. <br /><br />But here’s where the real cheese comes in. <b>Firstly, Mia herself is one of the blandest characters I’ve ever had the displeasure of reading about.</b> She fancies herself “not like the other girls”. She’s not like her family, guys. She plays <i>the cello</i> while the rest of her family (and her boyfriend) are the <i>punk rock</i> type.<br /><br />Audience: *Gasp!*<br /><br />Every time she said something along the lines of, “I don’t fit in. I like classical music,” I wanted to scream at her, “Mia, there’s people that are dying. You’ve got a lot more to worry about than your vs. your family’s musical preferences!”<br /><br />Speaking of her family. Her parents were rock stars back in their day, they knew what was hip-hop happening in the music world, and they continued to act like teenagers. They were the Cool Parents(™). And as for her brother, Teddy? They never squabbled, or argued, or fought even once. <b>It’s boring to read about a family dynamic that’s so effortlessly perfect</b>, but it’s also just plain unrealistic.<br /><br />Her boyfriend, Adam, was the dark punk-rocker boy-band-member caricature that makes me want to spew vomit. The makeout/sexytime scene where he was like, “Play me like your cello,” made me cringe so hard I very nearly entered another dimension. And to make matters worse, Mia <i>actually goes and gets her bow</i> and... Okay, I’ll stop. You guys don’t deserve that.<br /><br />The ending is painfully predictable. I knew that Mia would decide to stay from the first page, but that’s not what irked me most about the ending. Instead of Mia staying for herself, she stays for her boyfriend. The ending scene is him holding her hand and her trying to hold it back.<br /><br />I didn’t appreciate the romantic twist on the story. <b>I expected it to be more about Mia’s health and wellbeing, not her and Adam’s love for each other.</b> I just thought it was unbearably cheesy, and my eyes were dry the whole time.<br /><br /><s>Do I have a heart/soul? Probably not. </s><br /><br /><i>→ 2 stars</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="10734336514610937625" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


